        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To achieve our science goals, we need to detect the 158um [CII] line in the z=6.025 galaxy with at least S/N of 5. Since the [CII] line is redshifted to 158(1+z)um=1.1mm, and the target is a point source, we will use the Band 6 with the Extended Array. First, we calculated the [CII] line flux of ID9 based on the emprical relation between total SFR and [CII] line luminosity, which is calibrated by star-forming galaxies in the nearby universe (De Looze, I., et al. 2011, MNRAS, 416, 2712). The absolute UV magnitude of ID9 is -21.03 mag, which was derived from z'-band magnitude, correcting Ly-alpha line flux and intergalactic absorption (Madau, P. 1995, ApJ, 441, 18); the SFR is found to be 15.7 solar mass per year by Kennicutt, R. C. (1998, ARA&amp;A, 36, 189). Using this estimation, the [CII] line luminosity is expected more than 8.32e+41 erg/s. It should be noted that the dust-uncorrected SFR derived from UV luminosity was regared as total SFR; thus, the actual [CII] line luminosity will be higher. Based on this luminosity, the [CII] line flux can be calculated to be more than 2.07e-18 erg/s/cm^2 at z=6.025 (the luminosity distance is 1.79e+29 cm). Next, we assume that the line width of [CII] is the same as that of Ly-alpha, since these lines are emitted from the same region. As the FWHM of Ly-alpha is 8.2 angstrom, the frequency width of [CII] line would be 259.8 MHz. Therefore, the [CII] line flux density is 0.80 mJy. Since S/N&gt;5 is required to resolve emission lines, we set the desired sensitivity to be 0.16 mJy. We input 0.16 mJy to the Sensitivity Calculator of the ALMA Observing Tool. The band width is set to 50 km/s enough to resolve. We obtain 2.20 hour integration time on source. Thus, we request 4.34 hour, including overheads, of observation with ALMA. Meanwhile, since the SFR of ID5 is 6.6 solar mass per year, we can detect the [CII] line of ID5 with S/N&gt;2.1, simultaneously. According to the 1 sigma line sensitivity, atomic gas mass can be constrained less than 2.2e+8 solar mass if [CII] line is not detected.
In addition, we have estimated the sensitivity of continuum spectrum in this observation. We set 2.20 hour and 2 GHz to integration time and bandwidth, respectively. The 1 sigma continuum sensitivity was found to be 0.025 mJy for the rest-frame FIR continuum observation. From this sensitivity, dust mass can be estimated to be about 10^7 solar mass, assuming dust temperature to be 33K, which is derived from the highly lensed z=2.7 LBG (Baker, A. J., et al. 2001, A&amp;A, 372,L37). The estimation of dust mass depends on the dust temperture.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
