    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to carry out the ALMA [CII] line observation of an i'-dropout galaxy, which is the brightest protocluster galaxy (ID9) of the highest-redshift protocluster at z=6.0. Since this protocluster is expected to evolve into rich cluster, there already exists the progenitors of brightest cluster galaxies (BCGs). The stellar mass of ID9 was preliminary estimated as ten times higher than the average of other galaxies located in the protocluster region. Furthermore, ID9 has the highest star formation rate (SFR) in the protocluster region. Thus, this is the most promising progenitor of BCGs. In order to approach the mass build-up process of BCGs, we would like to estimate gas content and obscured SFR by detecting 158um [CII] emission line, which are key to evaluate how much star can be formed hereafter. The estimations of gas mass and total SFR will enable us to sort out how much self-active star formation or galaxy-galaxy merging contribute to mass assembly. Through the proposed observation, we can understand the baryonic content of a protocluster galaxy and discuss how protocluster galaxies will evolve toward the present universe.</prp:abstract>
